MoreInfo:
The United States’ National Emergencies often deal with domestic issues. 23 of the National Emergencies have had direct impacts on the United States. They include the following:

1. EMERGENCY IN WATER TRANSPORTATION OF THE UNITED STATES

President: Woodrow Wilson

Effective Dates: February 1917 - March 1921

Rationale: During World War I, Allied forces had a shortage of ships after German U-boat attacks. The private shipping industry was not efficient. The United States wanted to ensure troops, food, weapons, and other supplies could be transported to Europe. Under Proclamation 1354, Wilson gave the U.S. Shipping Board Emergency Fleet Corporation the ability to use privately owned boats and ships for war. The government took over water transportation so they could prioritize resources and production for war. This centralization influenced later transportation frameworks during times of emergency. This national emergency strengthened U.S. maritime power and expanded the war fleet.

2. DECLARING A BANK HOLIDAY

President: Franklin D. Roosevelt

Effective Dates: March 1933 - March 1933
